0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"markdown-container","children":[["$","h1","h1-0",{"children":"Sector Brief: Industrial Automation"}],"\n",["$","p","p-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Version"}],": 1.0 | ",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Date"}],": 2026-05-07"]}],"\n",["$","hr","hr-0",{}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-0",{"children":"1. Overview"}],"\n",["$","p","p-1",{"children":"Industrial automation is the use of control systems, such as computers or robots, and information technologies for handling different processes and machineries in an industry to replace a human being. It is a step beyond mechanization in the scope of industrialization, representing the systematic application of technology to control and optimize industrial processes."}],"\n",["$","p","p-2",{"children":"This sector is the bedrock of modern manufacturing, enabling the high-volume, high-quality production of goods across nearly every industry, from automotive to pharmaceuticals. The evolution of industrial automation can be traced through several distinct phases:"}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-0",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"First Generation (1960s-1980s)"}],": Mechanization with basic feedback control"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Second Generation (1980s-2000)"}],": Widespread PLC adoption and networking"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Third Generation (2000-2015)"}],": Integration of IT systems and MES"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-3",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Fourth Generation (2015-Present)"}],": Industry 4.0 with IoT, AI, and cloud connectivity"]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","p","p-3",{"children":"The market for industrial automation has grown to $200B+ globally, with 90%+ adoption in developed manufacturing sectors. Key performance indicators include Overall Equipment Effectiveness (OEE), Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF), and Mean Time To Repair (MTTR)."}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-1",{"children":"2. The Automation Pyramid (Purdue Enterprise Model)"}],"\n",["$","p","p-4",{"children":"Industrial automation is conceptualized using the Purdue Enterprise Reference Model (PERM), which organizes control systems into hierarchical levels from the enterprise down to the field devices:"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-0",{"children":"Level 4: Enterprise Level"}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-1",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Function:"}]," Business planning and logistics (ERP systems)"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Technologies:"}]," SAP, Oracle, Microsoft Dynamics"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Data:"}]," Business intelligence, financial planning, customer orders"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-3",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Communication:"}]," TCP/IP, HTTP, SQL databases"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-4",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Update Rate:"}]," Hours to days"]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-1",{"children":"Level 3: Site/Plant Level (MES)"}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-2",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Function:"}]," Manufacturing Execution Systems for production planning and scheduling"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Technologies:"}]," Wonderware, FactoryTalk, SIMATIC IT"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Data:"}]," Production schedules, material tracking, quality data"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-3",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Communication:"}]," TCP/IP, OPC, relational databases"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-4",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Update Rate:"}]," Minutes to hours"]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-2",{"children":"Level 2: Area/Workcell Level